24 Amend the amendment by striking out the emergency clause and substituting the
25 following:
26 'Emergency clause. In view of the emergency cited in the preamble, except for that
27 section of this Act that requires the Department of Health and Human Services to submit
28 the required methodology notice to seek approval from the United States Department of
29 Health and Human Services, Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services to implement a
30 cost-of-living adjustment of 1.95% in fiscal year 2024-25, which takes effect when this
31 legislation is approved, this legislation takes effect when the department seeks that
32 approval.'
33 Amend the amendment by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or
34 section number to read consecutively.
35 SUMMARY
3366 This amendment does the following.
37 1. It amends the training requirements for overseers, municipal officials designated by
38 an overseer or a municipal official appointed to administer municipal general assistance to
39 require training to be done annually and requires the Department of Health and Human
40 Services to provide information about the rules, requirements and compliance expectations
41 of the municipal general assistance program to those individuals.
Page 3 - 132LR2408(29)
SENATE AMENDMENT

SENATE AMENDMENT “ ” to COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “A” to H.P. 131, L.D. 209
1 2. It limits housing assistance under the municipal general assistance program, except
2 for temporary housing and emergency shelters, to a maximum of 12 months in a 36-month
3 period.
4 3. It requires the Department of Health and Human Services to submit the required
5 methodology notice to seek approval from the United States Department of Health and
6 Human Services, Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services to implement a cost-of-
7 living adjustment of 1.95% in fiscal year 2024-25 for reimbursement rates for certain
8 essential support workers. The department is required to submit the required methodology
9 notice no later than March 31, 2025 and to notify the Secretary of the Senate, the Clerk of
10 the House and the Revisor of Statutes when the department seeks the approval.
11 4. It requires the Department of Health and Human Services to contract, through a
12 competitive bidding process, with a 3rd-party independent entity to conduct a review of the
13 MaineCare program for fraud, waste and abuse, based on specified criteria, and to report
14 to the department with its findings no later than December 29, 2025. If the independent
15 entity fails to fulfill the requirements of the contract, the funds allocable to the portion of
16 the requirements that the independent entity failed to complete must be repaid to the
17 department.
18 5. It requires the Department of Health and Human Services to provide a report
19 regarding the findings of the review of the MaineCare program for fraud, waste and abuse
20 to the Joint Standing Committee on Appropriations and Financial Affairs by January 5,
21 2026, along with any necessary implementing legislation. The joint standing committee is
22 required to report out a bill to the Second Regular Session of the 132nd Legislature based
23 on the report.
24 6. It amends the emergency clause to specify that the entire Act, except for the piece
25 requiring the Department of Health and Human Services to submit the required
26 methodology notice to seek approval to implement the cost-of-living adjustment for
27 essential support workers, does not take effect until the department has sought that
28 approval.
